Iraq invaded Kuwait today, quickly seizing the palace and government buildings.
Iraq  said it invaded at the request of revolutionaries who had already staged a coup.
Kuwait's  emir fled to Saudi Arabia.
Kuwait's government appealed for U.S. military intervention.
The attack had wide-ranging ramifications:  Oil prices soared.
President Bush froze  Iraqi assets in the U.S. and blocked most Iraqi imports, including oil.
The Soviet Union  halted weapons sales to Iraq.
The U.N. Security Council denounced the invasion.
The  Pentagon diverted an aircraft carrier group toward the gulf.
Baghdad said it might  withdraw soon.
Borders were closed and foreigners were asked to lay low. 
